Scikit-Learn (sklearn) 
Scikit-Learn is an open-source machine learning library for Python. It is built on top of other popular libraries like NumPy, SciPy, and matplotlib. It provides simple and efficient tools for data mining, data analysis, and machine learning, making it one of the most widely used ML libraries.

✅ Main Features:
Simple & Consistent API

Efficient implementation of algorithms

Supports both supervised and unsupervised learning

Built-in tools for model evaluation and selection

Utilities for preprocessing data and feature engineering

✅ Key Components in Sklearn:
Supervised Learning Algorithms
Classification:

LogisticRegression, KNeighborsClassifier, SVC (Support Vector Classifier), DecisionTreeClassifier, RandomForestClassifier

Regression:

LinearRegression, Ridge, Lasso, SVR (Support Vector Regression), DecisionTreeRegressor

Unsupervised Learning Algorithms
Clustering:

KMeans, DBSCAN, AgglomerativeClustering

Dimensionality Reduction:

PCA (Principal Component Analysis), t-SNE

Model Selection
Cross-validation: cross_val_score

Hyperparameter tuning: GridSearchCV, RandomizedSearchCV

Metrics: accuracy_score, mean_squared_error, classification_report

Preprocessing
Scaling: StandardScaler, MinMaxScaler

Encoding: LabelEncoder, OneHotEncoder

Imputation: SimpleImputer

Splitting: train_test_split

Feature Selection & Extraction
SelectKBest

RFE (Recursive Feature Elimination)

✅ Typical Workflow in Sklearn
Load Dataset (CSV or from sklearn.datasets)

Preprocess (cleaning, encoding, scaling)

Split Data (train_test_split)

Choose Model (e.g., LogisticRegression())

Train Model (fit())

Predict (predict())

Evaluate (using metrics)

✅ Advantages of Scikit-Learn
Easy to learn and use

Well-documented

Huge community support

Integrates well with Pandas, NumPy, Matplotlib

Excellent for beginners and professionals

✅ Limitations
Not suitable for deep learning (use TensorFlow, PyTorch)

Limited to in-memory processing (not big data scale)

Less efficient for GPU processing
